1. Why asymptotic analysis is better

Asymptotic analysis is more useful because it evaluates performance independent of hardware, focusing on how algorithms scale as input size grows rather than relying on machine-specific timing.

2. Why Binary Search requires sorted data

Binary Search depends on ordering to eliminate half of the dataset each step without sorting it cannot determine which half to discard.

3. Nearly sorted array

Insertion Sort is better because it performs close to O(n) when data is already nearly sorted, making it much faster than Selection Sort.

4. Memory writes expensive

Selection Sort is better because it performs fewer swaps (writes), while Insertion Sort may shift many elements repeatedly.
